,Recommended,253650,12593140,"Posted: 21 October, 2014",all,Jadarma,"I have purchased this game on the one year anniversary, and 90% off a cheap title was an offer I could not refuse. The game is very fun. It consists of a casual simulation of an evolving life form you control that floats in water and tries to feed itself in order to evolve. The gameplay mechanic is somewhat reminescent of Spore's first stage. The graphics are dreamlike and the art style is impressive, the music sets the ambient rather well and the gameplay concept, although so simple and basic, manages to captivate you for a good few hours. Difficulty wise, the game is incredibly easy but it is meant to be a time-occupier (waster is innapropriate in this context), not a competitive game, although you have that option. While the game is fun, it lacks a few concepts that would have greatly improved it, and it kind of bugs me in a game that is concentrated on evolution: the lack of creature customization, as the creature grows soley based on what type of food you eat, and the lack of an endless mode, where the level is randomly generated. Other than that, it is a great game to spend your ""Im so bored"" time, and though not perfect, a great indie title."
,Not Recommended,253650,28515015,"Posted: 21 December, 2016",all,Titanic21,"Sparkle 2 Evo. The second part of the ""Sparkle-trilogy""; a series of so called ""Evolution simulations"". I own all three included ""games"" and I want to review them all.I have already recommended the first, no, the ""Zeroth"" (don´t know whether this word exists) part, because of it´s epic looks. Previous point is basically the mark of all three games; epic visuals but, well, questionable gameplay. Evo comes up to those too, but with some changes which disturbed me in some ways. So now I am heading to describe the game a little.There are just three aims in Sparkle 2 Evo:Eat, grow, evolve. That´s it. So for this nothing changes. And here comes the publishers´ ""clue"": Competetive mode. Yes, that´s as hillarious as it sounds. You are ""fighting"" against an AI in matches lasting WAY too long. The one eats more stuff ""wins"" and if that´s you, you´ll unlock the next stage, which is basically the same as the previous, just with new colors and soundtracks. Wait, there´s annother way to obtain your progress, next to competetive mode: You can also eat EVERY SINGLE PIECE OF NUTRIENS on the ENTIRE map. Because of the ""innovative"" controls, that are as precise as my aiming in CS:GO, (trust me, you don´t even want to see me using the AWP) that can easily take you 20 minutes of your precious lifetime. Okay, just joking, but not lying.Annother negativ fact are the ""enemies""... They CONTAIN the nutrients you need to win the level, but there´s always just one way to get them. And if you fail by half a visual milimeter, you´ll be pushed into annother layer of the ""Abyss"" (that´s what the game-world is called) over and over again... Unfortunately your AI oponnent has better luck with that.The only two things GOOD about this game are the visuals, as usual, and the fact you get the soundtrack for free. It´s not a extraordinary good one but at least a nice deal to compensate the EULA, which only says ""No EULA, just have fun""...Is there really need to discuss about this anymore?What I had almost forgotten to mention is, that Sparkle 2 was developed by other guys as Sparkle 3 and Zero were. They didn´t do a bad job (in relation to the other two games) but they also didn´t really make it better. As for normal, achievements are gained by progress and evolution isn´t only useless but also it does only depend on what color the food you eat has. Yeah, pretty much like in the other games.Sincerely, Titanic21; 21th December 2016; 9:12 pm; CET. (Just don´t take me too serious as for this review. My opinion is honest, but the rest is not.)"
