76561198160317251,Recommended,253650,17635179,"Posted: 20 August, 2015",all,Tea,"SHORT VERSIONPick it up for five euros and have a game that you can whip out for 20-30 minute sessions whenever you want to relax a bit.LONG VERSIONThe art is gorgeous and the beautifully animated sealife is sure to dazzle you at first glance. It comes with a soothing soundtrack to match its visual style. However, the gameplay is repetitive which is both the game's strong and weak point. It doesn't offer anything more beyond what you do in the first level (swim around, eat other organisms, sometimes evolve) but because of that it's  easy to understand and get into.The number of evolutions boil down to three (carnivore, herbivore, omnivore) per developmental stage so there's not much to play around with. You follow the pulsating lights to find food and once you have found it, you feed by simply swimming through it. You win by eating a set amount of food which can get tricky if you are a slowpoke and let other creatures nab your dinner. There are standard, static food such as algae and floating bits of meat but the higher level prey have fun little gimmicks to them. As an example, if you want to consume a baby squid you first need to snip away at its nervous system on the front then the poison glands on the back before it's weakened enough to be gobbled up.The best feature of the game is the inclusion of an optional non-competitive mode which removes the other hungry contestants so you can hunt for food at your own leisure."
