76561197971948490,Recommended,253650,12948415,"Posted: 15 November, 2014",all,Wraith_Magus,"This is a game that is meant to be played ""casually"".  While the game has multiple z-axis ""planes"", it is a game largely played on a 2-dimensional field, where you basically just guide your little critter to eat things until you grow up.  There are three ""paths"" to go down, which you traverse through eating colored blobs of three colors.There are two modes.In the non-competitive mode, you basically just get dumped on a map, and get told to eat everything of one color to go to the next map.  There's essentially no way to lose, but to quit, which I suppose is what makes it ""casual"", and it's not like games need to be hard to be enjoyable, but there's no particular story, here, to make the world more compelling without it.  There's some ""exploration"", just to see all the different critters, but once you have seen every level, you've seen everything the game has to offer.In the ""competitive mode"", you have an AI-controlled critter competing with you for food, where victory is measured in hogging more food than the other guy can get.  While hypothetically, this means challenge and desperately trying to hunt creatures for food faster, regardless of color, in practical effect, you can just stay green and vacuum up everything far faster than your opponent, since the extra bits of food from dividing food pieces all count to your total, and you can consume more food from critters than the game expects to count. In general, I could eat several times more food than the opponent, and never once seemed like I was in trouble unless I completely abandoned attempting to eat for a while.The big choice in the game about which critter to be is somewhat defeated by the imbalance in the practical use of the different criters.  The ""carnivore"" red is quick to accelerate, and gets a ""dashing"" skill to ""attack"" other creatures.  The ""herbivore"" green (and I put ""herbivore"" in quotes because you still hunt and eat other animals, you just want to eat the green ones) has faster eating time (making it so you can eat as fast as you ram through food, rather than skipping over food for a second or so) and has a super AoE suction attack that consumes all food in the area.  The ""omnivore"" blue (which, somehow, eats a different food entirely from both carnivores and herbivores, rather than just eating both in roughly equal measure,) gets a better turning radius and a defensive sound skill that makes creatures flee from it.Hypothetically, in a game where combat mattered, the difference between an attack skill, a defense skill, and a resource-gathering skill might mean something, but since all you do in this game is eat, the herbivore skill is fantastically useful and makes the game significantly faster and less frustrating, while the omnivore defenseskill is useless since you need to hunt critters, rather than have them flee you, and the carnivore dash attack is pointless since the only enemies that run from you do so across the z-axis, which the dash will not go across.Ultimately, I recommend this game only on sale for the sheer color and fascination of it.  It's odd and interesting, and worth looking at, and on sale, you can get it dirt cheap enough to justify buying it for aesthetics alone, but there isn't enough actual gameplay to keep you in it.  This is a game you can completely ""play out"" and feel you've experienced everything it can offer in just a half-dozen hours."
